HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 737
By Vital
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Robert Benson "Bob"
Brown.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Robert Benson "Bob" Brown; and
WHEREAS, Bob Brown was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, a native Tennessean born in Monterey on October 24, 1934, Bob Brown
was the son of E.C. and Gladys Brown and attended school in Monterey, graduating from high
school in 1952 and receiving awards for achievements in business and athletics; and
WHEREAS, an exceptional athlete, Mr. Brown led his high school football team, the
Monterey Wildcats, to the first state championship in school history; he later played third base
for a local baseball team, the Boys of Black Bottom, in games across Tennessee and Kentucky;
and
WHEREAS, a proud military veteran, Bob Brown enlisted in the U.S. Army in 1957 and
served his country until April 11, 1963, when he returned to civilian life and accepted
employment in Chattanooga; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Brown enjoyed a distinguished fifty-seven-year career with the
Tennessee Department of Transportation (TDOT), rising from his start as a day laborer to
ultimately become Regional Director for Region 2 of the State agency, a position he held until
his retirement in 2010; and
HJR0737
010839
- 1 -

WHEREAS, during his tenure at TDOT, he was involved in many projects in the twenty-
four county Region 2 area, including the construction of I-24 at Missionary Ridge in
Chattanooga and the construction of I-24 West at Monteagle Mountain in the 1960s; and
WHEREAS, to honor Mr. Brown's lifetime of service to the State of Tennessee, the 106th
Tennessee General Assembly passed Public Chapter 992 of 2010, which named the
administration building at the TDOT campus in Chattanooga the "Robert Brown Administration
Building"; and
WHEREAS, an active part of his community in Chattanooga, Bob Brown served as
president of the Tyner Youth Association for ten years in support of local youth sports and was
honored with the Dizzy Dean Man of the Year Award for the State of Tennessee in 1990; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Brown was also deeply devoted to his family, and he always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, Bob Brown is survived by his beloved wife, Shirley Vaughan Brown; his
daughter, Holly (Dewey) Williams; his son, Phillip (Pat) Vaughan, Jr.; his grandchildren, Drew
and Carlee Williams and Darby Williams; his great-grandchildren, Dallas, Case, and Chandler
Williams and Cain Howeth; his nephews, Jeff (Laura) Mitchell, Matthew Mitchell, and Corey
(Gina) Mitchell; his niece, Laney Mitchell; and a host of dear friends; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, he was preceded in death by his sisters, Shirley
B. Brewer and Mary Ann Mitchell; his brother-in-law, Ned Mitchell, Sr.; his nephew, Ned
Mitchell, Jr.; and his aunt, Bessie Brown, who was his greatest influence and mentor from his
earliest years; and
WHEREAS, Bob Brown leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
- 2 - 010839

WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Robert Benson "Bob" Brown, reflecting fondly
upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with
courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Brown.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
